### 4. Before/After Imagery Sources — Demo-Ready

**Free, no-attribution required (demo safe):**
- Unsplash driveway collection: https://unsplash.com/s/photos/driveway (8K+ images)
- Unsplash asphalt: https://unsplash.com/s/photos/asphalt (100+)
- Unsplash asphalt paving: https://unsplash.com/s/photos/asphalt-paving
- Unsplash cracked asphalt (ideal "before" image): https://unsplash.com/photos/cracked-asphalt-covers-the-entire-surface-MZgmNH6174Q
- Pexels driveway: https://www.pexels.com/search/driveway/ (8K+ images)
- Pexels asphalt: https://www.pexels.com/search/asphalt/ (20K+ images)

**Demo build strategy (avoids needing two separate images per project):**
Use CSS filter hack — single Pexels/Unsplash residential driveway photo; apply `filter: grayscale(80%) brightness(1.4)` for "before" (weathered/faded look) and full-color with `filter: brightness(0.85) saturate(1.2)` for "after" (fresh dark seal). The before-after slider JS library (e.g., `img-comparison-slider` web component or `before-after.js`) handles the drag interaction. This is hero-demo quality without needing real client photos.

**Reference contractor for real before/after visual style:** https://www.maintainitall.com/before-and-afters/sealcoating — shows authentic restoration results, useful for design direction.

**Production note (for proposal):** Tell client the live site will use their actual project photos; the demo uses stock imagery to illustrate the concept.

---

### 5. Additional Findings the Planner Should Know

**WordPress/tech stack concerns:**
- Client specified Bricks Builder + Rocket.net hosting — demo cannot replicate a real WP admin experience in a static iframe. The demo should be a pixel-accurate HTML/CSS/JS mockup of the FRONTEND (what visitors see), not a WP dashboard demo.
- The original posting mentions "Option 3: Docker + Tunnel" for a live WP demo — this is the approach for a REAL login-accessible demo. Client explicitly wants this: "For this I want to create a real WordPress website hosted on my backend and at my michaelwegter.com domain."
- This means demo-builder will need to: spin up WP via Docker on mw-backend's Surface machine, configure via WP-CLI, expose via Flask bridge tunnel, and deliver a real URL. This is significantly more complex than a static demo. Planner must explicitly scope this.

**Docker WP feasibility on mw-backend Surface:**
- Surface runner can execute Docker commands (Python script via surface_run.py)
- WP + MySQL Docker containers are well-supported on Windows
- WP-CLI available in the `wordpress:cli` Docker image
- Cloudflare tunnel already in place — a Flask bridge proxying to WP Docker container port (e.g., 8080) would work, BUT the tunnel config must not be modified (CLAUDE.md hard rule). Bridge blueprint at /demos/maryland-driveway-restore/* -> 127.0.0.1:8080 is the correct approach.
- Risk: Docker may not be installed on the Surface. Researcher cannot verify without running a surface_run check. Planner should flag this as a build-time verification step.

**SEO schema types needed (confirmed for plan):**
- LocalBusiness (or HomeAndConstructionBusiness subtype)
- Service schema per service page
- FAQPage schema (FAQ page)
- Review/AggregateRating schema
- BreadcrumbList
- WebSite with SearchAction

**Priority keywords confirmed (from brief):**
- "Maryland driveway restoration" (primary)
- "driveway restoration near me" (high-intent, mobile)
- "asphalt restoration Maryland"
- "driveway rejuvenation" (branded differentiator term)
- "blacktop restoration"

**QR Code landing page (/free-estimate):** Must be a distinct page/route, not the homepage. Include: 1 before/after image, 3-line value prop, phone CTA, text-a-photo CTA, minimal form. This is a Phase 1 deliverable per the brief (section 12).

